exDE is a software package that implements a mathematical framework for modular computation with structural flexibility for malaria and other mosquito-borne pathogens, as described in Spatial Dynamics of Malaria Transmission [1].

Design & Features

\(\oplus\)

exDE is a software package, developed by Sean L Wu and David L Smith, that implements modular computation for malaria and other mosquito-borne pathogens [1]. The library of dynamical components includes a large library of previously published models and algorithms. The mathematical framework was designed to be structurally flexible to facilitate nimble model building and the construction of ensembles with scalable complexity.

Epidemiology

\(\oplus\)

  • Xpar

  • Exposure in exDE the process of exposure and infection is handled as a generalized function that computes the FoI by strata as a function of the local EIR by strata and exposure to malaria while traveling

  • Dynamics general features of \(d{\cal X}/dt\)

  • Cohorts solving the dynamics of infection and immunity in cohorts of humans

  • Stratification the utilities established for principled stratification

Xpar

Exposure

  • Exposure and infection is handled by Exposure (in exposure.R) in steps:

    • the model computes a local EIR and passes it to Exposure

    • Exposure calls F_b to get a measure of the probability of infection, per infective bite, so the expected number of infective bites is \(b E\). The model F_b is dispatched by Xpar

    • the expected number of infective bites is transformed into a measure of the stratum specific local FoI, depending on the model for Environmental Heterogeneity

    • the travel FoI is added to the local FoI

Spatial Dynamics

Mosquito Ecology

Vector Control

Vector Control in exDE is implemented through a set of linked functions:

  • Distribution of commodities is handled through the function family called VectorControl

  • Coverage and the decay of efficacy (e.g. waning efficacy of insecticides, ownsership and condition of nets)

  • Human Behavior - dependent effects (e.g. bed net use)

  • Effects - we compute something like coverage and its effects on various parameters or variables (e.g. resource availability) in models that compute integrated effects

  • Effect Sizes - modifies parameters after a call to Bionomics introducing independent effect sizes that modify the parameters.

Forcing

exDE has a large set of built-in functions to describe exogenous forcing.

By default, exogenous forcing is turned off.

The list objects defining various kinds of forcing are in a nested hierarchy with several classes of base functions:

  • Malaria Importation is handled through travel and visitors.

  • Abiotic forcing by weather and hydrology

  • Civil factors, including shocks and economic development

  • Malaria Control of all sorts

  • Resources for mosquitoes can be dynamically changing, affecting the availability of aquatic habitats, blood, sugar, and resting sites.

Human demography including births, deaths, and migration is like mosquito ecology. It is part of the endogenous process, so it is handled in its own endogenous dynamic component, \(\cal H\).

If the class of a list object is null then there is no need to define anything of the objects it might contain. If a nested list objects is defined, then the list that contains it is turned on and set to forced. See Forcing for details.
